his fourth issue husband asserts that the trial courts conclusion of law concerning the community estates claims for reimbursement against his separate estate is erroneous ‚ÄÇ husband complains of cumulative error in his fifth issue ‚ÄÇ we affirmbackgroundhusband and wife were married on march   and permanently separated less than two and a half years later in october  ‚ÄÇ before their final separation the couple separated for six weeks during the summer of  ‚ÄÇ no children were born of or supported by the marriagehusband and wife were both in their thirties when they married ‚ÄÇ at that time wifes separate estate consisted primarily of the following ‚Äâemployee stock and an employee profitsharing plan worth approximately  equity of approximately  in a house and personal property ‚ÄÇ husband owned a house with equity of approximately  at the time of marriage as well as personal property ‚ÄÇ they chose to reside in wifes house and leased husbands houseboth husband and wife worked during the marriage ‚ÄÇ but although husband worked as an independent contractor in the airconditioner repair business he reported a net income of only  during the first year of marriage no income the second year and a net loss the third year ‚ÄÇ wife earned an average salary of  annually as a comptroller for the company for which she had worked for over  yearswife filed for divorce on june   and husband countersued three months later ‚ÄÇ neither petition asserted fault ‚ÄÇ the trial courts judgment separated the community estate by ordering that  wife and husband each be separately responsible for the attorneys fees they incurred during the divorce proceedings and that  the remainder of the community property be divided as shown belowwifes award of community propertywife received a value of  in assets that had been part of the community estate as follows‚Äâ the communityestate debt that was assigned to wife totaled  for the following debts ‚Äâfoleys for  first usa bank for  bank card service for  and capital one for  ‚ÄÇ after subtracting the community debt assigned to wife from the community assets awarded to wife wifes net award totaled husbands award of community propertyhusband received a value of  in assets that had been part of the community estate as followsonly two debts that belonged to the community estate first usa visa for  and chase platinum visa for  were awarded to husband for a total of  ‚ÄÇ thus the total net award for husband was the effect of the net distribution of the estate was approximately a  division of property in favor of wife in its conclusion of law number two the trial court stated that the ‚Äúdivision of the property of wife and husband effected by the final judgment is just and right having due regard for the rights of each party irrespective of the characterization of any item of property as either community or separate‚Äùdivision of community propertyin his first issue husband contends that the trial court abused its discretion by failing to divide the community estate in a just and right manner and by awarding an approximate  division of the community estate to wife after having previously stated that it would divide the property ‚Äúclose to a  split‚Äù ‚ÄÇ in issue two husband complains that the trial court awarded ‚Äúessentially all‚Äù of the community assets to wife and abused its discretion by failing to manifest a due regard for his rights‚ÄÉin a decree of divorce the court shall order a division of the community estate in a manner that the court deems just and right having due regard for the rights of each party ‚ÄÇtex famcode ann ¬ß‚ÄÇ vernon  ‚Äârafferty v finstad  swd   texapphouston st dist  writ denied ‚ÄÇ in effecting a just and right division of the community estate section  of the family code vests the trial court with broad discretion that will not be reversed on appeal unless the complaining party shows that the trial court clearly abused its discretion ‚ÄÇ murff v murff  swd   tex ‚Äârafferty  swd at  ‚ÄÇ the test of whether the trial court abused its discretion is whether the court acted arbitrarily or unreasonably and without reference to any guiding principles ‚ÄÇdowner v aquamarine operators inc  swd   tex ‚Äârafferty  swd at  ‚ÄÇ it is the duty of the appellate court to presume that the trial court properly exercised its discretion in dividing the marital estate ‚ÄÇmurff  swd at ‚ÄÉa trial court may order an unequal division of the community property when a reasonable basis exists for granting that relief ‚ÄÇ robles v robles  swd   texapphouston st dist  pet denied ‚ÄÇ the division of property must not be so disproportionate as to be inequitable and the circumstances must justify awarding more than onehalf to one party ‚ÄÇpatt v patt  swd   texapphouston st dist  no writ ‚ÄÇ relevant factors in the division of the marital estate include  the education of the parties  their relative earning capacities  the size of their separate estates and  the nature of the community property ‚ÄÇmurff  swd at  ‚Äâalsenz v alsenz  swd   texapphouston st dist  pet deniededucation of the parties‚ÄÉhusband has more formal education than wife he received a degree in agronomy turfgrass science from texas a  m university in  and education in airconditioning repair as a  graduate from houston community college ‚ÄÇ wife completed only one year of college following high school ‚ÄÇ because husbands formal education empowers him to obtain gainful employment at wages exceeding wifes this factor favors wifes receiving a greater share of the community propertyrelative earning capacityalthough wife earned more income than husband at an average wage of  annually the record suggests that husbands earnings could have exceeded wifes ‚ÄÇ husband could have earned much as  in the airconditioningrepair business alone but husband also had his own landscaping business and worked parttime in the carwash business ‚ÄÇ wifes salary appears to have peaked based on her employment for the past  years for the same company after working her way up from receptionist to comptroller ‚ÄÇ moreover wife testified that she may need to seek a lower position at the company and take a pay cut to reduce workrelated stress ‚ÄÇ because husband has the earning capacity to exceed wifes wages this factor favors wifes receiving a greater share of the community estatesize of separate estateshusband and wife both owned houses prior to marriage and wife had slightly more equity in her house when they married ‚ÄÇhusband also had more creditcard debt than wife at  ‚ÄÇ because of wifes employee stock and profitsharing plan however her separate estate greatly outweighs husbands ‚ÄÇthus although husband was capable of earning more money than wife due to his formal education wife had developed a considerably larger separate estate than husband before marriage ‚ÄÇ because wifes separate estate is more valuable than husbands this factor favors husbands receiving a greater share of the community propertynature of community propertyas reflected in the trial courts finding of fact number four the community estate consists primarily of the community interest in wifes employee stockownership plan valued at  and the profitsharing plan valued at  for a total of  ‚ÄÇ in addition the community estate had a total value of  for the community estates  claim for economic contribution for community funds spent to enhance the value of wifes house and the community estates claim for reimbursement for  from the separate estate of husband ‚ÄÇ the remaining community assets included the  dodge ram truck with an equity valued at  ‚Äâthe state farm life insurance policy valued at  ‚Äâand the washington mutual bank account valued at wife contends that she is entitled to a greater share of the community estate because she earned the vast majority of the income brought into the community estate ‚ÄÇ husband contends that wife interfered with his ability to work by imposing a curfew on him that required him to be home by  pm on weekdays and  pm on weekends ‚ÄÇ husband also contends that although his tax records show net losses he routinely deposited money into the community estate and gave the community estate the benefit of depreciation for some of his property in joint tax returns ‚ÄÇ wife denied placing a curfew on husband and claimed that he was voluntarily underemployed ‚ÄÇ we conclude that the trial court did not abuse its discretion by impliedly finding that this factor favors wifes receiving a greater share of the community propertyconclusionapplication of the murff factors supports the trial courts having properly exercised its discretion to award wife a greater share of the community estate in dividing the property in a ‚Äújust and right‚Äù manner ‚ÄÇ see murff  swd at  ‚ÄÇ the record shows that husband and wife are in their thirties that they are physically and mentally able and that each is capable of earning over  annually ‚ÄÇ although highly educated and capable of earning over  annually husband reported less than  in income during the marriage ‚ÄÇ the couple lived in wifes house and were supported by wifes income ‚ÄÇ wifes income paid for the benefits to wifes and husbands separate estates ‚ÄÇ under the circumstances the division of property was not so disproportionate as to be inequitable and the circumstances justify awarding more than half of the community estate to wife see patt  swd at ‚ÄÉin conducting a bench trial of a divorce case the trial court has the opportunity to observe the parties determine their credibility and evaluate their needs and potential both social and economic ‚ÄÇmurff  swd at  ‚ÄÇ similarly as the trier of fact the trial court is empowered to apply its understanding and experience ‚Äâmathematical precision in dividing property in a divorce is usually not possible ‚ÄÇid ‚ÄÇgiven the wide latitude and discretion vested in the trial court which we may disturb only in a case of clear abuse id we cannot conclude under the circumstances presented here that the trial court abused its discretion by awarding wife a greater share of the community estate‚Äúclose to a  split‚Äù‚ÄÉin support of his first issue husband further contends that because the trial court stated in its closing remarks that ‚Äúit works out that it is close to a  split and im going to leave the parties as they sit today‚Äù the trial court erred by instead dividing the property closer to a  division ‚ÄÇ the trial courts remarks however are not reflected in its findings of fact conclusions of law or judgment ‚ÄÇ accordingly they are not dispositive ‚ÄÇ see in re wer  swd   tex ‚ÄÇ rather the trial courts conclusions of law and judgment properly refer only to the just and right division of the property mandated by section  of the family code see tex famcode ann ¬ß‚ÄÇ ‚Äârafferty  swd at  ‚ÄÇ accordingly husbands contention does not conflict with our conclusion that the trial court did not abuse its discretion by awarding wife a greater share of the community estate in effecting its just and right distribution of the community estate‚ÄÉwe overrule husbands issue one ‚Äúessentially all‚Äù community assets to wife‚ÄÉin his second issue husband complains that wife was awarded ‚Äúessentially all‚Äù of the community assets ‚ÄÇ husband ignores that the community estates considerable debt was also assigned to wife although she received most of the community assets wife also received most of the community debt ‚ÄÇ accordingly we reject husbands contention that wife received ‚Äúessentially all‚Äù of the community assets and affirm our conclusion that the trial court did not abuse its discretion in its just and right distribution of the community estatewe overrule husbands issue tworeimbursement award against husbands estatethe reimbursement award stems from a claim by the community estate for compensation for community funds spent during the marriage on the house that husband owned before the marriage ‚ÄÇ in conclusions of law number four and five the trial court assessed a value of  for the reimbursement claim made by the community estate ‚ÄÇ the community estates entire reimbursement award valued at  was awarded to husband as his sole propertyhusband challenges the assessed value of  for the reimbursement claim in issue four ‚ÄÇ specifically husband claims that the record does not support the trial courts conclusions of law regarding the community estates claims for reimbursement against his separate estate and contends that the reimbursement award should be set aside‚ÄÉthe trial court entered findings of fact and conclusions of law in response to husbands request ‚ÄÇ husband did not offer proposed findings and did not propose additional or amended findings after the trial court adopted the findings proposed by wife see texr civ p   ‚ÄÇ in an appeal from a bench trial we review a trial courts conclusions of law as legal questions de novo and will uphold them on appeal if the judgment can be sustained on any legal theory supported by the evidence ‚ÄÇbmc software belgium v marchand  swd   tex ‚Äâin re moers  swd   texapphouston st dist  no pet ‚ÄÇ an appellant may not challenge a trial courts conclusions of law for factual sufficiency but we may review the legal conclusions drawn from the facts to determine their correctness ‚ÄÇbmc software belgium  swd at  ‚ÄÇ if we determine that a conclusion of law is erroneous but that the trial court nevertheless rendered the proper judgment the error does not require reversal ‚ÄÇid‚ÄÉwhen as here the appellate record contains a complete reporters record we review the trial courts findings of fact under the same standards for legal and factual sufficiency that govern review of jury findings ‚ÄÇ see min v avila  swd   texapphouston st dist  no pet ‚ÄÇ the trial court acts as factfinder and is the sole judge of the credibility of witnesses in a bench trial ‚ÄÇ see murff  swd at  ‚Äâsouthwestern bell media inc v lyles  swd   texapphouston st dist  writ denied ‚ÄÇ accordingly the trial court may consider all the facts and circumstances in connection with the testimony of each witness and accept or reject all or part of that testimony ‚ÄÇ an appellate court may not substitute its judgment for the trial courts assessment of witnesses testimony in a bench trial ‚ÄÇ see in re wer  swd at ‚ÄÉwhen the trial courts findings of fact address a ground of recovery or defense but inadvertently omit an essential element we may infer the omitted element pursuant to rule  of the rules of civil procedure because the judgment is presumed valid ‚ÄÇ see texr civ p  ‚Äâvickery v commn for lawyer discipline  swd   texapphouston th dist  pet denied ‚Äâsee also vickery  swd at  noting that presumptive validity of judgment may apply even more strongly in bench trial ‚ÄÇ we emphasize moreover that the value of specific items of property is not an ultimate issue in the trial courts property division and does not require specific fact findings by the trial court ‚ÄÇrafferty  swd at husband challenges the following two conclusions of law‚ÄÉ the community estate has claims for reimbursement against the separate estate of husband in the amount of ‚ÄÉas part of a just and right division of the assets and liabilities of the marriage husband is awarded the community property claim against his separate property of husband challenges the conclusions of law concerning the reimbursement claim on the following grounds ‚Äâ wife offered no evidence to support her claim for  in improvements to his house ‚Äâ the total paid by the community towards his house was  rather than  ‚Äâ the trial court did not offset  in benefits to the community estate from rent of husbands house and  the trial court did not offset benefits valued at  for depreciation of his house that was taken on the couples  joint tax return ‚ÄÇ the trial court entered findings of fact and conclusions of law but addressed these issues solely in its conclusions of law without entering separate findings‚ÄÉin a decree of divorce the court shall determine the rights of both spouses in a claim for reimbursement and shall apply equitable principles to  determine whether to recognize the claim after taking into account all the relative circumstances of the spouses ‚Äâand  order a division of the claim for reimbursement if appropriate in a manner that the court considers just and right having due regard for the rights of each party ‚ÄÇtex famcode ann ¬ß‚ÄÇb  vernon  ‚ÄÇ the trial courts discretion in evaluating a claim for reimbursement is as broad as its discretion to effect a just and proper division of the community estate ‚ÄÇpenick v penick  swd   tex ‚Äâalsenz  swd at ‚ÄÉa party claiming the right of reimbursement must plead and prove that the expenditures and improvements were made and that they are reimbursable ‚ÄÇvallone v vallone  swd   tex ‚ÄÇ the trial court must consider the facts and circumstances and determine what is just fair and equitable ‚ÄÇpenick  swd at  ‚ÄÇ the trial court is accorded great latitude in applying equitable principles to value a claim for reimbursement ‚ÄÇid at ‚ÄÉclaims for reimbursement may be offset against each other if the court determines that this is appropriate ‚ÄÇtex famcode ann ¬ß‚ÄÇc vernon  ‚ÄÇ a trial court is required to consider offsetting benefits when a litigant requests that relief ‚ÄÇgutierrez v gutierrez  swd   texappsan antonio  no writfact findings support a reimbursement claim for an additional on reviewing the record we discern that finding of fact number nine supports a reimbursement claim to the community estate valued at  rather than the  that was awarded in conclusions of law numbers four and five ‚ÄÇ according to finding of fact number nine the community disbursed  in community funds for husbands separate property as follows ‚Äâ for insurance taxes and mortgage payments on husbands house  for improvements to husbands house  for supplies for husbands house  for utilities for husbands house  for repairs to husbands house  fo